Percona Random Query Generator (RQG): GIS Grammars
==================================================
This directory contains a suite of grammar (.yy) files specifically designed to 
test the Spatial/GIS extensions within Percona Server for MySQL and MySQL-compatible 
databases. These grammars have been optimized for compatibility across version branches

Grammar Overview
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Grammar File          Complexity    Setup Requirement        Description
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
gis_functional.yy     Basic         schema.sql               Standard functional testing of basic geometry types 
                                                             (POINT, POLYGON). Ideal for quick smoke tests.
                                                             
linestring.yy         Targeted      osm_to_sql.py            Focuses on LINESTRING and MULTILINESTRING operations. 
                                                             Uses real-world OSM data to test spatial index hints.
                                                             
gis.yy                Advanced      Self-contained           High-complexity stress testing. Includes nested 
                                                             functions, collections, and spatial relations.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Execution Details

1. gis_functional.yy
	The gis_functional.yy grammar relies on tables created by the schema.sql file. 
	You must use the --post-gendata-sql flag to instruct the RQG to execute the SQL setup 
	after it completes the initial data generation phase but before it starts the query loop.

	perl runall-new.pl \
  	  --basedir=$BASEDIR \
  	  --vardir=$VARDIR \
  	  --post-gendata-sql=conf/gis/schema.sql \
  	  --grammar=conf/gis/gis_functional.yy \
  	  --threads=2 \
  	  --queries=10000

	To use custom schema, Pipe the WKT file through the wkt2sql.pl script to obtain SQL

2. linestring.yy
	Running the linestring.yy grammar is a data-driven process. 
	This grammar is designed to test how the optimizer handles real-world spatial data distributions.

	Use the osm_to_sql.py script to fetch data from OpenStreetMap for any city.
	  python3 osm_to_sql.py "Kanyakumari" linestring.sql --mysql-version 5.7

	perl runall-new.pl \
	  --basedir=$BASEDIR \
	  --vardir=$VARDIR \
	  --post-gendata-sql=conf/gis/linestring.sql \
	  --grammar=conf/gis/linestring.yy \
	  --threads=2 \
	  --queries=10000

3. gis.yy
  	Running the gis.yy grammar is the most straightforward. It is designed to be self-contained. 
	It does not require external SQL files or Python pre-processing scripts; instead, it relies 
	on the RQG's internal random generators to produce both the spatial data and the queries. 

	perl runall-new.pl \
  	  --basedir=$BASEDIR \
  	  --vardir=$VARDIR \
  	  --grammar=conf/gis/gis.yy \
  	  --threads=2 \
  	  --queries=10000


Copyright notices on the map data
=================================

Due to licensing incompatibility, map data is not part of the RQG source
tree. It can be downloaded from https://overpass-turbo.eu/

The map data is (c) OpenStreetMap contributors and has a CC-BY-SA license. See

http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/OpenStreetMap_License
